overnment often attempts to satisfy the incompatible preferences of a two-faced public.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aPolitical participationzUnited States. 0aPolitical psychologyzUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 4aPhilosophy : Pragmatism. 4aPolitics and Law : American Politics. 4aPolitics and Law : Democracy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Behavior. 4aPublic Policy : Public Opinion. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847242340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438472423423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438472423/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles